
@startuml

class Country {
  - countryName: String
  - vatRate: Double
  - currency: String
  - euroConversionRate: Double
}

class Product {
  - productName: String
  - description: String
  - netPrice: Double
  - manufacturer: String
  - country: Country
}

class Representative {
  - firstName: String
  - lastName: String
  - socialSecurityNumber: String
  - telephone: String
  - email: String
  - country: Country
}

class Customer {
  - name: String
  - address: String
  - telephone: String
  - email: String
  - countriesReselling: Set<Country>
}

class Order {
  - orderId: String
  - quantity: Integer
  - orderDate: Date
  - desiredDeliveryDate: Date
  - product: Product
  - representative: Representative
}

Country "1" *-- "0..*" Product : sells
Country "1" *-- "1" Representative : responsible for
Customer "1" *-- "0..*" Country : resells in
Representative "1" --> "1" Order : places
Product "1" --> "1" Order : ordered
Order "1" --> "1" Customer : belongs to (implicit)

@enduml

---

### Explanation of Key Relationships:

- **`Country` ↔ `Product`**: A country may sell multiple products, but a product is sold only in one country.
- **`Country` ↔ `Representative`**: Each representative is responsible for exactly one country.
- **`Customer` ↔ `Country`**: A customer can resell in multiple countries.
- **`Representative` ↔ `Order`**: Each order is placed by exactly one representative.
- **`Product` ↔ `Order`**: Each order refers to exactly one product.
- **`Order` ↔ `Customer`**: An order belongs to a customer (not explicitly modeled here, but implied).

